Indonesia Stocks: Charoen Pokphand, Intiland Development, Medco

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-24T09:19:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-24/indonesia-stock-movers-charoen-pokphand-intiland-development.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  fell 33.44 points, or 0.9
percent, to 3,847.02.  PT Charoen Pokphand Indonesia (CPIN IJ), a poultry farm
operator, climbed 1.8 percent to 2,850 rupiah, the highest close
since Aug. 4. The company hired four banks to help it borrow
$200 million, according to two people familiar with the matter.
The proceeds will be used to refinance debt and for capital
expenditure, one of the people said.  PT Intiland Development (DILD IJ), a property developer,
rose 5.3 percent to 300 rupiah, the sharpest increase since Aug.
10. Intiland got a 400 billion rupiah ($47 million) loan from PT
Bank Bukopin to increase its capital expenditure, Bisnis
Indonesia reported, citing Archied Noto Pradono, a director at
the company. Corporate Secretary Theresia Rustandi couldn’t be
reached when called at her office in Jakarta.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),  Indonesia ’s
biggest listed oil company, declined 1 percent to 2,425 rupiah.
A Medco and PT Pertamina project on Monday halted output at its
Tiaka oil field in Central Sulawesi province after about 30
protesters attacked and damaged production facilities, energy
regulator BPMigas said. The Tiaka oil field produces 1,600
barrels a day, BPMigas said.  PT Myoh Technology (MYOH IJ), a  software developer  for
hotels and restaurants, jumped 34 percent to 90 rupiah, capping
an 80 percent two-day surge. Bisnis Indonesia reported on its
website today the company plans to switch its business into coal
mining. President Director Dedet Yandrinal couldn’t be reached
when called at his office in Malang, Central Java.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
